    A-Team

    University Offices

    Website Mission Membership Benefits

    Contact: Email group officers

    Mission
    The A-Team includes members from each Student Affairs department who is interested in expanding their assessment skills and knowledge, assist in building a culture of assessment in the division and enhancing our practice around data informed decision making. No previous experience in assessment is needed to be a member, just a willingness to join in a community of people interested in learning.

    Membership Benefits
    Members of the newly forming Student Affairs Assessment team will:
    • Participate in training that empowers departments and individuals to enhance current assessment practices.
    • Learn new assessment strategies and techniques that can applied on current or future projects.
    • Share assessment resources across a larger group of colleagues.
    • Assist with creating and implementing a division-wide assessment planning process and timeline.
    • Serve as a liaison to their department regarding assessment best practices and learning opportunities.
    • Build collaborations across the division where assessment efforts can be combined.

    Lifetime membership

  • Active Ally

    University Offices

    Website Mission Membership Benefits

    Mission
    Welcome to the Binghamton University Active Ally Page! The Binghamton University Active Ally Program is a leadership development program seated in LGBTQ+ competency education to help support Faculty, Students, and Staff in becoming Active Change Agents to better support and advocate for LGBTQ+ people and all of their intersections.

    This page serves as the entry point for the program and its community. For students, Here you will find our schedule of events updated for each semester. For our employees, please head over to the UCTD Training Calendar to see all our trainings scheduled each semester. (https://calendar.google.com/calendar/u/1/embed?src=binghamton.edu_0i2ao47pakbhni7tuisvpg6lo0@group.calendar.google.com&ctz=America/New_York)

    If you have any questions, please contact the Q Center at lgbtq@binghamton.edu or call our office at 607-777-6028.

    Membership Benefits
    Currently, this page is in development to help continue the work outside of our sessions. Future goals include monthly/weekly newsletters with articles and new opportunities to expand Allyship skills, weekly prompts and readings from around the community and the world, and forums for support in your journeys as Active Allys.

    Please be sure to check back often for updates on what is going on and if you would like to help out, please contact the Q Center at lgbtq@binghamton.edu.

  • Asian Student Union

    SA Organizations - Cultural, Social

    Website Mission

    Contact: Email group officers

    Mission
    Asian Student Union (ASU) is one of the largest cultural organizations in Binghamton University (SUNY). Representing roughly 20% of its Asian and Asian American undergraduate/graduate students, ASU along with our seven subgroups, serve to defy stereotypes, define culture, maintain a sense of tradition, and what it is to be Asian American in today's world.

    Our subgroups include Asian Outlook (AO), Binghamton University Japanese Association (BUJA), Chinese American Student Union (CASU), Korean American Student Association (KASA), Philippine-American League (PAL), Taiwanese American Student Coalition (TASC), and Vietnamese Student Association (VSA).

    ASU and its subgroups host events that uplift the diverse community that is representative of the Asian/American and Pacific Islander community. Varying from annual cultural showcases such as "Asian Night" and Barrio to night markets, food-making and craft-making workshops, becoming a general body member of one organization means that you join them all.

    Come join the ASU family today! Follow us on Instagram (@binghamtonasu) and Facebook (@asu.binghamton) to see what we do day to day or send us your email so we can add you to our list-serv. Every week we send an email listing our events for the week and other announcements.

    Membership Benefits

    Lifetime membership

  • Binghamton Fujianese Union

    Website Mission

    Mission
    The objective of the Fujianese Union (FJU) is to increase the cultural awareness of Fujianese culture among Binghamton University students and the campus at large. FJU will focus on the unique traditions observed within Fujianese culture. FJU will encourage and support the diversity of the university by uniting all people who share an interest in learning, respecting, and comprehending Fujianese culture and the Fujianese experience. It would provide Fujianese individuals a home away from home, thereby helping them stay connected with their roots. It's important to note that the majority of our Chinese students are from Fujian/have a Fujianese background, yet they know very little of their culture and traditions since their unique culture has been condensed into a broad, oversimplified "Chinese" identity.

    Success Coaching

    Mission
    Peer and professional Success Coaches support student learning through personalized one-on-one coaching appointments, workshops and access to virtual resources. They are trained to identify potential barriers to academic success and collaboratively construct a tailored success plan for each student. Success plans are meant to be worked through in one semester and include topics such as:

    effective goal setting
    time management
    study strategies and test preparation skills
    organization
    productivity management

    In addition to these focus areas, the Success Coaching staff also works closely with campus partners to serve as a source of direct referrals to all student services. If they are not able to assist with a particular challenge, they connect students with the best qualified campus partner to address the situation.

    Harpur Harpeggios

    SA Organizations - Performance

    Website Mission

    Contact: Email group officers

    Mission
    The Harpur Harpeggios, fondly known as "The Pegs," comprise the only soprano-alto a cappella group at Binghamton University in Vestal, New York. The Pegs typically consist of eight to twenty members (though the size is not restricted to these numbers). Anyone who can sing soprano and/or alto voice parts is welcome to audition for the Pegs, regardless of gender identity. The Pegs, formed in 1983, was spawned by one visionary member of the Harpur Chorale. They have since grown to compete internationally in multiple ICCA (International Competition for Collegiate A Cappella Championships) tournaments, be featured on the social media of Kelly Clarkson and Atlantic Records, and even perform on the Radio City Music Hall stage to open for the Rockettes' Christmas Spectacular.

  • Juvenile Urban Multicultural Program

    SA Organizations - Academic

    Website Mission

    Contact: Zoe Peterson, Email group officers

    Mission
    The Juvenile Urban Multicultural Program (J.U.M.P. Nation), is a student-run, non-
    profit organization comprised of volunteers attending the State University of New York at Binghamton. With a mission to decrease the high school drop out rate through mentoring, while increasing student enrollment into institutions of higher education, J.U.M.P. Nation helps supply at-risk middle school students with the necessary tools to help them overcome socio-economic issues and gives Binghamton University student the rare opportunity to help support and guide the academic success and personal vision of youth. The founders of J.U.M.P. Nation believed that the most effective way to help combat problems such as the combination of social, political, and economic factors that might prevent or deter students from reaching their educational goals and receiving the type of quality education they deserve, was to motivate students to pursue higher education at an early age. Thus, to achieve the goals set forth by our mission statement, J.U.M.P. Nation selects approximately 100 students, called prot├®g├®s, to participate in a four day, all-expense-paid weekend program at Binghamton University. Prot├®g├®s are paired with Binghamton University students with the hopeful intention of promoting higher education as a viable objective and the hopeful intention of providing them with influential individuals who encourage the fulfillment of their goals. As a network of support that helps them overcome obstacles throughout their high school careers, while simultaneously introducing them to an environment of higher education, Binghamton University students are presented with the rare and rewarding opportunity to make a positive difference in the life of underprivileged youth who have been neglected, unrecognized, and ignored.

    Membership Benefits

    Lifetime membership

    Mu Sigma Upsilon Sorority, Inc.

    Fraternities and Sororities - Multicultural Greek and Fraternity Council

    Website Mission Membership Benefits

    Contact: Aileen Zambrano Cruzatty

    Mission
    In 1981, our founding mothers saw the need for a sorority that crossed the societal boundaries of race, religion, culture, and class. While other Greek organizations are and continue to grow more diverse, our organization foundation is based on diversity and our sisters embrace multicultural ideals and interests; we speak to use our sorority as a vehicle to educate the surrounding campus and community on issues of diversity.

    We recognize that diversity is not limited to race, and we are proud to say we have achieved a sisterhood which is quite diverse with respect to not only race, but religious heritage, geographic origin, sexual orientation, socioeconomic class, nationality, political ideology, and even choice of major and career.

    Ultimately, multiculturalism is the belief that there is inherent value in discovering, understanding, and appreciating all the ways in which people are different from each other. It is for this reason that we differentiate ourselves, in name and in purpose, from Greek organizations with the word "MUlticultural".

    Membership Benefits
    Joining Mu Sigma Upsilon Sorority, Inc. has benefits beyond sisterhood and graduation. These include but are not limited to life-long sisterhood, leadership opportunities, academic support, personal and professional development, networking, etc.

    SA Organizations - Social/Recreational, Cultural

    Website Mission

    Contact: Email group officers

    Mission
    The National Association of Black Accountants is a pre professional organization designed to address the needs of underrepresented students interested in various business disciplines; and promote the development of skills and talents central to successful careers in the future. B.M.M.M.O, which is now known as NABA, was founded in 1981, on the Binghamton University Campus by Anthony Kendall, who is currently the CEO of Mitchell and Titus, LLP.
    We hold seminars, and workshops, as well as recruit professional speakers from all business fields in order to execute our mission. One of our paramount events for the year is attending the National Association of Black Accountants (NABA) conference. The NABA conference helps prepare students for a future in corporate America. The conference consists of a four-day weekend packed with networking with hundreds of professionals and students in the business field, while enhancing job-searching opportunities.
    In addition, we partake in numerous community service events, and host an annual banquet where students receive the opportunity to network with Binghamton alumni, while enjoying themselves with dinner and entertainment.
    The objective of the National Association of Black Accountants is to address the needs of minority students interested in the various management disciplines and to promote the skills and characteristics central to successful careers within these disciplines.

  • Nu Alpha Phi Fraternity

    Fraternities and Sororities - Asian Greek Council, Cultural, Social

    Website Mission

    Mission
    The fraternity professes to create a bond of brotherhood passed down from generation to generation, including lasting relationships between alumni and currently active members.

    Externally, it seeks to promote Asian-awareness, as well as to serve as a liaison between the Greek community and the Asian community. This is done through a supportive network of alumni and matriculated brothers who actively engage in participation in community service, cultural workshops and events, university programs, and various other on-campus student activities. Additionally, the fraternity strives to work with various other Asian Greek organizations in an effort to bring unity and recognition to the Asian-American community.

    Internally, the fraternity emphasizes brotherhood and promotion of self-development for all of its members, as encouraged by its seven fundamental principles of brotherhood, discipline, leadership, pride, professionalism, service, and unity. Members are taught to use these principles in everyday life to promote personal growth. These ideals are brought upon prospective members, as well.

    Additionally, the fraternity promotes brotherhood through events such as alumni networking, job banks, sports competitions, and road trips. The fraternity actively seeks to integrate its members into the local community through social events, on-campus performances, and participation in various cultural organizations.

    Although the fraternity asserts itself as an Asian-interest organization, it openly welcomes members from any ethnicity or cultural background, and its membership has continued to increase in diversity over the years.

  • One Health Medical Association

    SA Organizations

    Website Mission Membership Benefits

    Contact: Kristi Cheung, Kyle Cheung, Email group officers

    Mission
    One Health Medical Association (OHMA) serves as an interdisciplinary space for Binghamton University students to collaborate between peers and professionals from various health disciplines to create an innovative and holistic approach to achieve One Health: the concept that human, animal, and environmental health are interconnected and that collective organized involvement across all fields of expertise (i.e., physicians, veterinarians, research scientists) is necessary to recognize solutions to complex shared health threats. OHMA seeks to provide opportunities for career development, network with professionals in One Health fields, and foster community and communication to create advocates with the goal of creating a transdisciplinary partnership between healthcare, animals, and the environment to advance medicine and public health.

    Membership Benefits
    One Health Medical Association is a group of students who are dedicated to the concept that the health of people is closely connected to the health of all species and our shared environment. We support the global One Health Initiative and are dedicated towards unity between professionals from various health disciplines to create an innovative and holistic approach to improve health and make a positive impact on our planet. We serve as a forum for discussion and a source of information on issues facing animals, peoples, and places in hopes of spreading awareness and training Binghamton students to become advocates for these issues. We recognize development as a professional to be our core focus through organized involvement and collaboration between physicians, veterinarians, research scientists, and more to gain insight and more clearly define the complex interconnections between sustainability, global biodiversity, personal ethics, and public health. We welcome all interested students and faculty to join our initiative and invite newcomers to help expand our mission!

    Lifetime membership

  • She's the First

    SA Organizations - Social

    Website Mission

    Contact: Email group officers

    Mission
    She's the First provides scholarships to girls in low-income countries, fostering first-generation graduates and cultivating the next generation of global leaders. She's the First works closely with international, locally-driven NGO partners to identify scholars at primary and secondary school levels based on financial need, scholastic merit, and their potential to become positive influencers and leaders within their communities. Harnessing technology and social media, She's the First is committed to connecting student campus leaders, scholars, and activists around the world in innovative, mutually beneficial ways to foster mentorship, philanthropy, equality, and leadership.

    She's the First currently has partners in ten countries: India, Nepal, Guatemala, Peru, Tanzania, Kenya, Uganda, The Gambia, Ethiopia, and South Sudan. The educational philosophy is that quality always trumps quantity, and there is an emphasis on each girl's right to self-determination across these opportunities. Each scholar is given tools and resources to ensure her success, during and after her school years. The scholars learn more than basic academics; they learn how to apply their new skills to the world around them, encouraged by support systems and mentors every step of the way. Ultimately, student leaders and scholars become change agents who will break cycles of generational poverty and transform our world.

    This group will benefit Binghamton students by giving them a global perspective on girls' education, a topic that is rapidly increasing in awareness, but still requires passionate advocates. Being a part of She's the First is about more than fundraising—it is about working together to create a huge collective impact that reaches far beyond the walls of a school building. This group's work is essential to achieving education equality for girls around the world.

    Membership Benefits

    Lifetime membership

  • SUNY Kids

    SA Organizations - Philanthropy/Community Service

    Website Mission

    Contact: Email group officers

    Mission
    SUNY Kids is a volunteer organization that takes kids from low income areas of Broome County on day trips every Saturday. Most of the children come from foster homes and are appointed to us through the Broome County Department of Social Service. We help provide a fun, safe environment for the children to enjoy as well as to learn. Some activities that we do include: roller blading, apple-picking, Discovery Center, bowling, etc.

    Membership Benefits

    We'd love to have you volunteer with us! Our organization takes children from the Binghamton area on field trips every Saturday from 11:30am to 4pm to places like The Discovery Center, Ross Park Zoo, Check E Cheese, etc.. We meet at the student Union, and take a school bus to our trips from there. Everything, admissions, food, transportation, is paid for by us!

    To secure a spot on one of our trips, I will send an email out to the entire listserv, and it's first come first serve. Whoever responds first gets to come on a trip! So be looking out for our email.

    In addition, in order to volunteer with us you need to fill out our volunteer application, and attach a printed picture of your student ID to it. Then bring this to our SUNY Kids mailbox in the SA office (which is in University Union West, behind Visions and the bookstore).

    So email us today at sunykids@binghamtonsa.org so you receive our listserv emails and retrieve a copy of our volunteer application!

    Hope to see you on our next trip!

    Lifetime membership

    The Source Project

    University Offices

    Website Mission

    Mission
    The Source Project is a sequence of two, four-credit courses called research streams that take place in fall and spring semesters of a student's first year. Students have the opportunity to discover sources and interpret their signficance. They ask questions and seek answers, guided by experienced faculty who engage in these practices as their profession. Students produce original projects that express their findings and learn how to communicate and disseminate the relevance of what they have found.

    The Source Project is an excellent opportunity to connect with other first-year peers who share similar interests. This experience provides a dynamic and engaging small class environment that encourages the building of meaningful connections with both fellow students and professors.

    Throughout their year in the Source Project, students not only gain impactful knowledge, they become the sources of knowledge themselves.
